Running a business as an introverted creative who is very private should not be complicated, yet it often is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with the big (and devilish) tech companies using extraverted techniques. Promote yourself here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service checked, be available 24/7, seven days a week, answer questions with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
01/03/2024
It is a year of transition for me.
I don't want to feed the big technology companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Nor do I want to have coaches who have only one solution for extroverts that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my work while fighting against the idea I've long believed in, that there's a certain way things must be done in order to succeed.
Wish me good luck!
I've already gone through the first steps.
I left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday, and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a CRM based in Europe for better compliance with the GDPR, and I will be transferring my operations over the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX records to Proton and I'm now fully utilizing SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
